collation.p: Originally, the manuscript was probably made up of quires of ten leaves, four paper bifolia around one inner parchment bifolium. Fourteen such quires are still extant.

history.provenance: The inclusion of the feast for the relics of Uppsala cathedral, , suggest that the breviary was intended for the diocese of Uppsala. A former librarian has suggested a church in Sigtuna, see .
history.acquisition: Bought together with a similar manuscript, A 102, at the Kyckerström auction in Uppsala 28 March 1855, according to notes in the library archives, see . It was listed as item no. 6 and cost 1 RB 1 b skr Bko.

msItem.title: Proper of time (fragmented)
msItem.explicit: quia hic est vere propheta qui venturus est in mundum psalmus Magnificat et cetera

note.p: Almost the whole Proper of time is missing on account of lost quires and pages.
contains readings, probably for the First and Second Saturday after Epiphany. They are excerpts from sermons by Ps. Augustine and Ps. Maximus.

contain readings for the feast De prophetis (the beginning is missing); contain readings from Ezek. 2-7 for Sundays and weekdays; contain readings and collects for the twenty-five Sundays after Trinity. Despite the inserted dummy-leaves no text is missing between and nor between and .

On two texts have been added in different contemporary hands. The first contain instructions on how to procede if there are more than twenty-five sundays after Trinity, the second on how to celebrate the Octave for St Andrew.

msItem.title: Proper of saints (fragmented)
msItem.rubric: In vigilia beati andree apostoli si dominica fuerit legatur omelia dominicalis alioquin de vigiliis Secundum Iohannem
msItem.incipit: In illo Stabat Iohannes et ex discipulis eius duo (John 1:35)
msItem.explicit: nec prius dignum iudicauit cetu ecclesie donec publicam ageret penitentiam Tu autem domine

note.p: The Proper of saints begins with the Vigil for St Andrew and ends with St Linus.
The bottom part of is damaged making it impossible to ascertain that the text for St Linus is complete.

An unknown number of leaves are missing after , which contains the readings for the third nocturn for St Anne (9 Dec.). The Proper continues on , which should precede , with the end of the feast of the Purification (2 Feb.). All feasts between 9 Dec. and 2 Febr. are thus missing.
No loss of text between and despite inserted dummy-pages.

On the Proper of saints ends after what seems to be the fourth reading for St Ambrose (4 April). It is followed by the Common for one martyr in two versions depending on the degree of solemnity. The proper continues on with Sts Tiburtius and Valerianus (14 Apr.). Notable feasts:
: St Anne (9 Dec.);
: St Botvid (28 July);
: Feast for the relics;
: St Birgitta (7 Oct.).

msItem.title: Suffrages
msItem.rubric: Hic notatur suffragia que habenda sunt in sabbatis de patronis primo in vesperis de sancto laurencio per antiphona
msItem.explicit: versus Ora pro nobis collecta omnipotens sempiterne de reliquis sicut in vesperis
msItem.note: Two sets of suffrages each, for Saturdays and Christmas, for St Lawrence, St Erik, St Henrik and the relics.

msItem.title: Readings
msItem.rubric: De beata virgine in sabbatis legenda Sermo beati augustini Sabbato primo
msItem.incipit: Adest nobis dilectissimi dies venerabilis virgini dedicatus
msItem.note: This sections contains sermons by Augustine, Jerome, Bernhard of Clairvaux, Maximus and Fulbert of Chartres. There are quite a few agreements with the readings in Breviarium Upsalense (printed) 1496 as regards the texts on 150v-154v.

supportDesc.condition: Binding, whole quires and single leaves are missing. Some leaves must have been missing already in the fifteenth century, since leaves with the missing text have been supplied, see e.g. . The extant quires are loose and the condition of the quires and leaves is poor. The paper is brittle and shows signs of corrosion from the ink. Parts are missing from some leaves, e.g. , . A preservation was made in 1974, which is probably when some pages were reinforced and a number of dummy-pages added for support. Some leaves have become unordered in the conservation process and dummy-pages have sometimes been inserted where no leaves are missing, giving the impression that text has been lost, see description in Contents.
